n's U.S. operations.<ref name=AmnestyBio/> She has published several articles related to [[small arms trade|small arms trading]] as well as human rights issues in North Africa. She is considered an expert on [[Tunisia]], [[Morocco]] and [[Algeria]], and her publications have appeared in academic journals including [[World Policy Journal]] and [[Human Rights Quarterly]].<ref name=MichFaculty/>    She is co-author of the website Human Rights Advocacy and the History of International Human Rights Standards, hosted by University of Michigan.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.fordschool.umich.edu/faculty/Susan_Waltz Faculty page, University of Michigan]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Waltz, Susan}}\n[[Category:American political scientists]]\n[[Category:International relations scholars]]\n[[Category:Josef Korbel School of International Studies people]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Denver alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Michigan faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Michigan people|Faculty]]\n[[Category:Gerald R. Ford School of Public Policy faculty]]\n[[Category:Amnesty International people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{US-polisci-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1996-1998 \u2192 1996\u20131998", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Susan_Waltz"}
{"title_page": "Sally Terry", "text_new": "'''Sarah \u201cSally\u201d Meiklejohn Terry''' (born 1937) was a political science professor at [[Tufts University]] beginning in the fall of 1975<ref name=\"Resolution\">{{cite web|title=Resolution on the retirement of Sarah Meiklejohn Terry|url=https://ase.tufts.edu/faculty/pdfs/retiredFaculty/terry.pdf|publisher=Tufts University|accessdate=5 February 2018}}</ref> until her retirement on December 31, 2002.<ref name=\"Tufts\">{{cite web|title=Sarah Meiklejohn Terry|url=http://as.tufts.edu/politicalscience/sites/all/themes/asbase/assets/documents/emeritusTerry.pdf|publisher=Tufts University|accessdate=5 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nA native of [[Newton, Massachusetts]], Terry graduated with a BA from [[Cornell University]] ([[Phi Beta Kappa]] and [[Phi Kappa Phi]]). She went on to receive her M.A. and a Ph.D. from [[Harvard University]] in Soviet Studies and Political Science, respectively.<ref name=\"Resolution\" />\n\n==Bibliography==\n*''Poland\u2019s Place in Europe: General Sikorski and the Origin of the Oder-Neisse Line, 1939-1943'' (Princeton University Press, 1983) won the American Historical Association's George Louis Beer Prize in Modern European International History<ref name=\"Resolution\" />\n*Terry has edited and contributed to ''Soviet Policy in Eastern Europe'' (Yale University Press, 1984) and co-edited and contributed to ''The Soviet Empire Reconsidered: Essays in Honor of Adam B. Ulam'' (Westview Press, 1994)<ref name=\"Tufts\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Terry, Sarah}}\n[[Category:Tufts University faculty]]\n[[Category:Cornell University alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Newton, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:Women political scientists]]\n\n{{US-polisci-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Sarah \u201cSally\u201d Meiklejohn Terry''' (born 1937) was a political science professor at [[Tufts University]] beginning in the fall of 1975<ref name=\"Resolution\">{{cite web|title=Resolution on the retirement of Sarah Meiklejohn Terry|url=https://ase.tufts.edu/faculty/pdfs/retiredFaculty/terry.pdf|publisher=Tufts University|accessdate=5 February 2018}}</ref> until her retirement on December 31, 2002.<ref name=\"Tufts\">{{cite web|title=Sarah Meiklejohn Terry|url=http://as.tufts.edu/politicalscience/sites/all/themes/asbase/assets/documents/emeritusTerry.pdf|publisher=Tufts University|accessdate=5 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nA native of [[Newton, Massachusetts]], Terry graduated with a BA from [[Cornell University]] ([[Phi Beta Kappa]] and [[Phi Kappa Phi]]). She went on to receive her M.A. and a Ph.D. from [[Harvard University]] in Soviet Studies and Political Science, respectively.<ref name=\"Resolution\" />\n\n==Bibliography==\n*''Poland\u2019s Place in Europe: General Sikorski and the Origin of the Oder-Neisse Line, 1939-1943'' (Princeton University Press, 1983) won the American Historical Association\u2019s George Louis Beer Prize in Modern European International History<ref name=\"Resolution\" />\n*Terry has edited and contributed to ''Soviet Policy in Eastern Europe'' (Yale University Press, 1984) and co-edited and contributed to ''The Soviet Empire Reconsidered: Essays in Honor of Adam B. Ulam'' (Westview Press, 1994)<ref name=\"Tufts\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Terry, Sarah}}\n[[Category:Tufts University faculty]]\n[[Category:Cornell University alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Newton, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:Women political scientists]]\n\n{{US-polisci-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBibliography:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sally_Terry"}
{"title_page": "Katherine Tate", "text_new": "{{For|the English actress and comedian|Catherine Tate}}\n{{Orphan|date=February 2013}}\n\n'''Katherine Tate''' (born November 8, 1962) is an [[Americans|American]] [[Political science|political scientist]] best known for her research on race and ethnic minority politics. She is a professor of Political Science at Brown University.\n\n==Biography==\nTate received her B.A. in political science from the [[University of Chicago]] in 1983, and her M.A. in 1985 from the [[University of Michigan]].  She completed her Ph.D. in political science from Michigan in 1989.<ref>[http://www.faculty.uci.edu/profile.cfm?faculty_id=3222 UCI Faculty Profile]</ref>  After working at [[Harvard University]]<ref>[https://www.jstor.org/pss/1963940 American Political Science Review, 1991]</ref><ref>[https://www.jstor.org/pss/419439 PS:Political Science and Politics, 1992]</ref> and serving as an associate professor of political science at [[Ohio State University]]<ref>[https://www.amazon.com/Protest-Politics-American-Elections-Foundation/dp/0674325400 Book Jacket, 1994]</ref> she became a professor of Political Science at the [[University of California, Irvine]].<ref>[http://www.faculty.uci.edu/profile.cfm?faculty_id=3222 UCI Faculty Profile]</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\nTate is the author or co-author and co-editor of six books.\n*{{citation|first=Katherine|last=Tate|year=1993|title=From Protest to Politics:  The New Black Voters in American Elections|location=Cambridge, MA|publisher=Harvard University Press and the Russell Sage Foundation}}. Enlarged edition, 1994. This book was the winner of two book prizes, the Southern Political Science Association's 1994 V.O. Key Jr. book award and the National Conference of Black Political Scientists\u2019 1995 Outstanding Book Award.  \n*{{citation|authorlink1=Lucius Barker|first1=Lucius J.|last1=Barker|first2=Mack H.|last2=Jones|first3=Katherine|last3=Tate|year=1999|title=African Americans and the American Political System|edition=4th|location=Englewood Cliffs, NJ|publisher=Prentice Hall}}.\n*{{citation|first=Katherine|last=Tate|year=2003|title=Black Faces in the Mirror: African Americans and Their Representatives in the U.S. Congress|location=Princeton, NJ|publisher=Princeton University Press}}. This book won the 2004 V.O. Key Jr. book award, and was the co-winner of the 2004 Race, Ethnicity, and Politics Section book award and the 2005 co-winner of the National Conference of Black Political Scientists\u2019 Outstanding Book Award. It was also named an outstanding academic title by Choice Magazine. \n*{{citation|first=Katherine|last=Tate|year=2010|title=What\u2019s Going On?  Political Incorporation and the Transformation of Black Public Opinion|location=Washington, DC|publisher=Georgetown University Press|isbn=9781589017023}}.\n*{{citation|first1=Katherine|last1=Tate|first2=James Lance|last2=Taylor|first3=Mark Q|last3=Sawyer|year=2013|title=Something's In the Air:  Race, Crime, and the Legalization of Marijuana|location=New York, NY|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-415-84240-2}}.\n* Tate, Katherine. (2013). Concordance:  ''Black Lawmaking in the U.S. Congress from Carter to Obama''.  Ann Arbor, MI:  University of Michigan Press. {{ISBN|978-0-472-11905-9}}.\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n*http://www.faculty.uci.edu/profile.cfm?faculty_id=3222&term_list=tate\n* https://www.nytimes.com/roomfordebate/2011/07/25/how-budget-cuts-will-change-the-black-middle-class/cuts-are-palatable-because-some-blacks-are-in-office\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tate, Katherine}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Chicago alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Michigan alumni]]\n[[Category:University of California, Irvine faculty]]\n[[Category:American political scientists]]\n[[Category:Women political scientists]]\n\n{{US-polisci-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{For|the English actress and comedian|Catherine Tate}}\n{{Orphan|date=February 2013}}\n\n'''Katherine Tate''' (born November 8, 1962) is an [[Americans|American]] [[Political science|political scientist]] best known for her research on race and ethnic minority politics. She is a professor of Political Science at Brown University.\n\n==Biography==\nTate received her B.A. in political science from the [[University of Chicago]] in 1983, and her M.A. in 1985 from the [[University of Michigan]].  She completed her Ph.D. in political science from Michigan in 1989.<ref>[http://www.faculty.uci.edu/profile.cfm?faculty_id=3222 UCI Faculty Profile]</ref>  After working at [[Harvard University]]<ref>[https://www.jstor.org/pss/1963940 American Political Science Review, 1991]</ref><ref>[https://www.jstor.org/pss/419439 PS:Political Science and Politics, 1992]</ref> and serving as an associate professor of political science at [[Ohio State University]]<ref>[https://www.amazon.com/Protest-Politics-American-Elections-Foundation/dp/0674325400 Book Jacket, 1994]</ref> she became a professor of Political Science at the [[University of California, Irvine]].<ref>[http://www.faculty.uci.edu/profile.cfm?faculty_id=3222 UCI Faculty Profile]</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\nTate is the author or co-author and co-editor of six books.\n*{{citation|first=Katherine|last=Tate|year=1993|title=From Protest to Politics:  The New Black Voters in American Elections|location=Cambridge, MA|publisher=Harvard University Press and the Russell Sage Foundation}}. Enlarged edition, 1994. This book was the winner of two book prizes, the Southern Political Science Association\u2019s 1994 V.O. Key Jr. book award and the National Conference of Black Political Scientists\u2019 1995 Outstanding Book Award.  \n*{{citation|authorlink1=Lucius Barker|first1=Lucius J.|last1=Barker|first2=Mack H.|last2=Jones|first3=Katherine|last3=Tate|year=1999|title=African Americans and the American Political System|edition=4th|location=Englewood Cliffs, NJ|publisher=