{"title_page": "Lester Spence", "text_new": "'''Lester K. Spence''' (born June 5, 1969), Professor of Political Science and Africana studies at [[Johns Hopkins University]] is known for his academic critiques of [[neoliberalism]] and his media commentary and research on race, urban politics, and [[police violence]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://politicalscience.jhu.edu/directory/lester-spence/ |title=Lester Spence |publisher=The Department of Political Science, Johns Hopkins University|date= |accessdate=2015-07-22}}</ref>  He was previously an Assistant Professor of Political Science at [[Washington University]], St. Louis. Spence's writings on race and politics appear regularly in publications such as ''[[Jacobin (magazine)|Jacobin]]'', ''[[The Chronicle of Higher Education]]'',[http://chronicle.com/article/Police-Violence-Out-of/237236] [[Dissent (American magazine)|''Dissent'' ]]<ref>https://www.dissentmagazine.org/author/lester-spence</ref>[[NPR]],<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.npr.org/2015/07/17/423740596/is-obama-finally-becoming-the-president-african-americans-wanted |title=Is Obama Finally Becoming The President African-Americans Wanted? |publisher=NPR |date=2015-07-17 |accessdate=2015-07-22}}</ref>''[[New York Times]]'', ''[[Baltimore City Paper]]'', among others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citypaper.com/special/bcp-2015-resolutions-for-baltimore-lester-spence-20150106-story.html |title=2015 Resolutions for Baltimore: Lester Spence - Baltimore City Paper |publisher=Citypaper.com |date=2015-01-09 |accessdate=2015-07-22}}</ref>  Spence also appears regularly on ''C-SPAN'', [http://www.steinershow.org/podcasts/dr-lester-spences-knocking-the-hustle-against-the-neoliberal-turn-in-black-politics/ The Marc Steiner Show], among others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citypaper.com/special/bcp-2015-resolutions-for-baltimore-lester-spence-20150106-story.html |title=2015 Resolutions for Baltimore: Lester Spence - Baltimore City Paper |publisher=Citypaper.com |date=2015-01-09 |accessdate=2015-07-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.c-span.org/video/?325683-6/washington-journal-lester-spence-americas-inner-cities |title=Washington Journal Lester Spence America's Inner &#124; Video |publisher=C-SPAN.org |date=2015-05-07 |accessdate=2015-07-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/opinion/lester-spence-baltimore-time-bomb-article-1.2202502 |title=Lester Spence: Why Baltimore was a time bomb |publisher=NY Daily News |date=2015-04-29 |accessdate=2015-07-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/roomfordebate/2015/01/01/is-the-modern-american-dream-attainable/for-black-people-there-is-martin-luther-kings-dream |title=For Black People, There Is Martin Luther King's Dream |publisher=NYTimes.com |date=2015-01-01 |accessdate=2015-07-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.npr.org/2012/01/16/145185983/can-hip-hop-change-the-style-of-politics |title=Can Hip-Hop Change The Style Of Politics? |publisher=NPR |date=2012-01-16 |accessdate=2015-07-22}}</ref>\n\nRaised in [[Inkster, Michigan|Inkster]], Spence holds both a BA and a PhD in Political Science from the [[University of Michigan]]. He has lived in [[Baltimore]] since 2004 and is a father of five.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ev-speak.com/portfolio-type/dr-lester-k-spence/ |title=Dr. Lester K. Spence &#124; Elite Voices |publisher=Ev-speak.com |date=2012-04-04 |accessdate=2015-07-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721172007/http://www.ev-speak.com/portfolio-type/dr-lester-k-spence/ |archive-date=2015-07-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n*Spence, Lester. ''Knocking the Hustle: Against the Neoliberal Turn in Black Politics.'' Punctum Books, 2016.\n*Spence, Lester. \"Race, Class, and the Neoliberal Scourge.\" Tikkun 28, no. 4 (2013): 29\u201331.\n*Spence, Lester K. \"Race and The Green Mile.\" Contours of African American Politics: Black Politics and the Dynamics of Social Change 2 (2012): 281.\n*Spence, Lester, and Mike McGuire. \"Occupy and the 99%.\" We are Many: Reflection of Movement Strategy From Occupation to Liberation AK Press (2012): 53\u201365.\n*Spence, Lester K. Stare in the darkness: The limits of hip-hop and Black politics. U of Minnesota Press, 2011.\n*Spence, Lester K., and Harwood McClerking. \"Context, black empowerment, and African American political participation.\" American Politics Research 38, no. 5 (2010): 909\u2013930.\n*Spence, Lester K. \"Episodic frames, HIV/AIDS, and African American public opinion.\" Political Research Quarterly 63, no. 2 (2010): 257\u2013268.\n*Spence, Lester K., Harwood K. McClerking, and Robert Brown. \"Revisiting black incorporation and local political participation.\" Urban Affairs Review (2009).\n*Spence, Lester. \"The Deaths Could Have Been Prevented.\" Space and Culture 9, no. 1 (2006): 5\u20136.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{C-SPAN|Lester Spence}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Spence, Lester}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American political scientists]]\n[[Category:University of Michigan College of Literature, Science, and the Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:Johns Hopkins University faculty]]\n\n\n{{US-polisci-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Lester K. Spence''' (born June 5, 1969), Professor of Political Science and Africana studies at [[Johns Hopkins University]] is known for his academic critiques of [[neoliberalism]] and his media commentary and research on race, urban politics, and [[police violence]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://politicalscience.jhu.edu/directory/lester-spence/ |title=Lester Spence |publisher=The Department of Political Science, Johns Hopkins University|date= |accessdate=2015-07-22}}</ref>  He was previously an Assistant Professor of Political Science at [[Washington University]], St. Louis. Spence's writings on race and politics appear regularly in publications such as ''[[Jacobin (magazine)|Jacobin]]'', ''[[The Chronicle of Higher Education]]'',[http://chronicle.com/article/Police-Violence-Out-of/237236] [[Dissent (American magazine)|''Dissent'' ]]<ref>https://www.dissentmagazine.org/author/lester-spence</ref>[[NPR]],<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.npr.org/2015/07/17/423740596/is-obama-finally-becoming-the-president-african-americans-wanted |title=Is Obama Finally Becoming The President African-Americans Wanted? |publisher=NPR |date=2015-07-17 |accessdate=2015-07-22}}</ref>''[[New York Times]]'', ''[[Baltimore City Paper]]'', among others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citypaper.com/special/bcp-2015-resolutions-for-baltimore-lester-spence-20150106-story.html |title=2015 Resolutions for Baltimore: Lester Spence - Baltimore City Paper |publisher=Citypaper.com |date=2015-01-09 |accessdate=2015-07-22}}</ref>  Spence also appears regularly on ''C-SPAN'', [http://www.steinershow.org/podcasts/dr-lester-spences-knocking-the-hustle-against-the-neoliberal-turn-in-black-politics/ The Marc Steiner Show], among others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citypaper.com/special/bcp-2015-resolutions-for-baltimore-lester-spence-20150106-story.html |title=2015 Resolutions for Baltimore: Lester Spence - Baltimore City Paper |publisher=Citypaper.com |date=2015-01-09 |accessdate=2015-07-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.c-span.org/video/?325683-6/washington-journal-lester-spence-americas-inner-cities |title=Washington Journal Lester Spence America's Inner &#124; Video |publisher=C-SPAN.org |date=2015-05-07 |accessdate=2015-07-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/opinion/lester-spence-baltimore-time-bomb-article-1.2202502 |title=Lester Spence: Why Baltimore was a time bomb |publisher=NY Daily News |date=2015-04-29 |accessdate=2015-07-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/roomfordebate/2015/01/01/is-the-modern-american-dream-attainable/for-black-people-there-is-martin-luther-kings-dream |title=For Black People, There Is Martin Luther King's Dream |publisher=NYTimes.com |date=2015-01-01 |accessdate=2015-07-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.npr.org/2012/01/16/145185983/can-hip-hop-change-the-style-of-politics |title=Can Hip-Hop Change The Style Of Politics? |publisher=NPR |date=2012-01-16 |accessdate=2015-07-22}}</ref>\n\nRaised in [[Inkster, Michigan|Inkster]], Spence holds both a BA and a PhD in Political Science from the [[University of Michigan]]. He has lived in [[Baltimore]] since 2004 and is a father of five.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ev-speak.com/portfolio-type/dr-lester-k-spence/ |title=Dr. Lester K. Spence &#124; Elite Voices |publisher=Ev-speak.com |date=2012-04-04 |accessdate=2015-07-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721172007/http://www.ev-speak.com/portfolio-type/dr-lester-k-spence/ |archive-date=2015-07-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n*Spence, Lester. ''Knocking the Hustle: Against the Neoliberal Turn in Black Politics.'' Punctum Books, 2016.\n*Spence, Lester. \"Race, Class, and the Neoliberal Scourge.\" Tikkun 28, no. 4 (2013): 29-31.\n*Spence, Lester K. \"Race and The Green Mile.\" Contours of African American Politics: Black Politics and the Dynamics of Social Change 2 (2012): 281.\n*Spence, Lester, and Mike McGuire. \"Occupy and the 99%.\" We are Many: Reflection of Movement Strategy From Occupation to Liberation AK Press (2012): 53-65.\n*Spence, Lester K. Stare in the darkness: The limits of hip-hop and Black politics. U of Minnesota Press, 2011.\n*Spence, Lester K., and Harwood McClerking. \"Context, black empowerment, and African American political participation.\" American Politics Research 38, no. 5 (2010): 909-930.\n*Spence, Lester K. \"Episodic frames, HIV/AIDS, and African American public opinion.\" Political Research Quarterly 63, no. 2 (2010): 257-268.\n*Spence, Lester K., Harwood K. McClerking, and Robert Brown. \"Revisiting black incorporation and local political participation.\" Urban Affairs Review (2009).\n*Spence, Lester. \"The Deaths Could 